column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There were approximately 2500 export and 410 young cattle penned representing a decrease of 36 head week-on-week. The usual buying group was present and operating in a dearer market. Quality was good with fewer dairy lots in the bullocks while the trade offering was very mixed. Well finished trade cattle lilted 10c to 15c/kg while secondary lots were cheaper. Grown steers sold firm while bullocks gained 5c/kg. Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers improved 15c to 23c with the crossbred portion firm to 8c/kg dearer. Heavy beef cows gained 5c to 10c while light conditioned dairy lots kicked 20c to 30c/kg. Heavy bulls lifted 5c/kg. 

Vealers sold from 250c to 408c/kg. Yearling trade steers made between 335c and 370c/kg. Yearling heifers to the trade sold between 310c and 355c/kg. Grown steers made from 335c to 380c/kg. Bullocks sold from 350c to 403c/kg. 

Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers made between 272c and 342c with the crossbred portion between 280 and 372c/kg. Most light and medium weight cows sold between 205c and 256c/kg. Heavy weight cows made mostly from 243c to 298c/kg. Heavy bulls sold from 270c to 316c/kg. 

Market reporter: Brendan Fletcher.
